    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "For version numbers, I recommend you follow the Semantic Versioning specification, https://semver.org/\r\n\r\nI usually use GitVersion to generate the SemVer numbers, https://github.com/GitTools/GitVersion.\r\n\r\nSo \"Nethermind/1.3.0-beta.3\" is a lower version than \"Nethermind/1.3.0\". The \"-\" is for pre-release identifiers, and \"+\" for build information (and there is no \"v\").\r\n\r\nBuild metadata can be anything, e.g. SHA is common \"Nethermind/1.3.0+421312f2\". Originally I had just the commit SHA, but recently I changed it to also include commits since base: \"0.3.0+180.Sha.c848961\"; easy enough to change back.\r\n\r\nNote that the version comes from the DLL, inserted during the build, so no code change. But looking at your build scripts, I think the publishing is in build-runner.sh and doesn't specify the version, or seem to update values (such as the old AssemblyInfo.cs), but I could be wrong. In Runner.csproj there is a before build target that seems to manually grab the git hash. So maybe it uses that and doesn't insert version numbers into the DLL.\r\n\r\nGitVersion will automatically generate the version according to the branch, e.g. for pre-release, etc, depending on the scheme used.\r\n\r\nSee the build.ps1 in the master of my old repo for how to use and grab the output of GitVersion and use it to set the values during dotnet publish.\r\n\r\nI will talk to Mateusz about maybe including it in the build scripts, and confirming if you include build numbers.\r\n\r\n",
